{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778987935077,"sessionID":"ses_1cc16f0e6ffekDdP0f8Ru75kV9","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_Jqk7MIMqtlnpwue06Q8X4q4B","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/references_cache/PMID_33243852.md","offset":1,"limit":140},"output":"<path>/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/references_cache/PMID_33243852.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: reference_id: PMID:33243852\n3: title: Human NLRP1 is a sensor for double-stranded RNA.\n4: authors:\n5: - Bauernfried S\n6: - Scherr MJ\n7: - Pichlmair A\n8: - Duderstadt KE\n9: - Hornung V\n10: journal: Science\n11: year: '2021'\n12: doi: 10.1126/science.abd0811\n13: keywords:\n14: - \"Adaptor Proteins, Signal Transducing/chemistry, metabolism\"\n15: - \"Adenosine Triphosphatases/chemistry, metabolism\"\n16: - Adenosine Triphosphate/metabolism\n17: - Alphavirus Infections/immunology\n18: - Animals\n19: - \"Apoptosis Regulatory Proteins/chemistry, metabolism\"\n20: - HEK293 Cells\n21: - Host-Pathogen Interactions/immunology\n22: - Humans\n23: - Hydrolysis\n24: - \"Immunity, Innate\"\n25: - \"Inflammasomes/immunology, metabolism\"\n26: - \"Keratinocytes/immunology, metabolism, virology\"\n27: - Mice\n28: - \"Mice, Transgenic\"\n29: - NLR Proteins\n30: - Protein Domains\n31: - \"RNA, Double-Stranded/metabolism\"\n32: - \"RNA, Viral/metabolism\"\n33: - \"Semliki forest virus/immunology, physiology\"\n34: - Virus Replication\n35: content_type: abstract_only\n36: ---\n37: \n38: # Human NLRP1 is a sensor for double-stranded RNA.\n39: **Authors:** Bauernfried S, Scherr MJ, Pichlmair A, Duderstadt KE, Hornung V\n40: **Journal:** Science (2021)\n41: **DOI:** [10.1126/science.abd0811](https://doi.org/10.1126/science.abd0811)\n42: \n43: ## Content\n44: \n45: 1. Science. 2021 Jan 29;371(6528):eabd0811. doi: 10.1126/science.abd0811. Epub\n46: 2020  Nov 26.\n47: \n48: Human NLRP1 is a sensor for double-stranded RNA.\n49: \n50: Bauernfried S(1), Scherr MJ(2), Pichlmair A(3)(4), Duderstadt KE(2)(5), Hornung \n51: V(6)(2).\n52: \n53: Author information:\n54: (1)Gene Center and Department of Biochemistry, Ludwig-Maximilians-Universität \n55: München, Munich, Germany.\n56: (2)Max-Planck Institute of Biochemistry, Martinsried, Germany.\n57: (3)Institute of Virology, Technical University of Munich, School of Medicine, \n58: Munich, Germany.\n59: (4)German Center for Infection Research (DZIF), Munich, Germany.\n60: (5)Physics Department, Technical University of Munich, Garching, Germany.\n61: (6)Gene Center and Department of Biochemistry, Ludwig-Maximilians-Universität \n62: München, Munich, Germany. hornung@genzentrum.lmu.de.\n63: \n64: Comment in\n65:     Mol Cell. 2021 Feb 4;81(3):423-425. doi: 10.1016/j.molcel.2021.01.001.\n66: \n67: Inflammasomes function as intracellular sensors of pathogen infection or \n68: cellular perturbation and thereby play a central role in numerous diseases. \n69: Given the high abundance of NLRP1 in epithelial barrier tissues, we screened a \n70: diverse panel of viruses for inflammasome activation in keratinocytes. We \n71: identified Semliki Forest virus (SFV), a positive-strand RNA virus, as a potent \n72: activator of human but not murine NLRP1B. SFV replication and the associated \n73: formation of double-stranded (ds) RNA was required to engage the NLRP1 \n74: inflammasome. Moreover, delivery of long dsRNA was sufficient to trigger \n75: activation. Biochemical studies revealed that NLRP1 binds dsRNA through its \n76: leucine-rich repeat domain, resulting in its NACHT domain gaining adenosine \n77: triphosphatase activity. Altogether, these results establish human NLRP1 as a \n78: direct sensor for dsRNA and thus RNA virus infection.\n79: \n80: Copyright © 2021 The Authors, some rights reserved; exclusive licensee American \n81: Association for the Advancement of Science. No claim to original U.S. Government \n82: Works.\n83: \n84: DOI: 10.1126/science.abd0811\n85: PMID: 33243852 [Indexed for MEDLINE]\n\n(End of file - total 85 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nreference_id: PMID:33243852\ntitle: Human NLRP1 is a sensor for double-stranded RNA.\nauthors:\n- Bauernfried S\n- Scherr MJ\n- Pichlmair A\n- Duderstadt KE\n- Hornung V\njournal: Science\nyear: '2021'\ndoi: 10.1126/science.abd0811\nkeywords:\n- \"Adaptor Proteins, Signal Transducing/chemistry, metabolism\"\n- \"Adenosine Triphosphatases/chemistry, metabolism\"\n- Adenosine Triphosphate/metabolism\n- Alphavirus Infections/immunology\n- Animals\n- \"Apoptosis Regulatory Proteins/chemistry, metabolism\"\n- HEK293 Cells","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"references_cache/PMID_33243852.md","time":{"start":1778987935067,"end":1778987935075}},"id":"prt_e33f1a5530019D7PNw6mUPC0vC","sessionID":"ses_1cc16f0e6ffekDdP0f8Ru75kV9","messageID":"msg_e33f16bca001fdx5OWwvCajYcx"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1778987935131,"sessionID":"ses_1cc16f0e6ffekDdP0f8Ru75kV9","part":{"id":"prt_e33f19168001eOXvaYGhsv7OHX","messageID":"msg_e33f16bca001fdx5OWwvCajYcx","sessionID":"ses_1cc16f0e6ffekDdP0f8Ru75kV9","type":"text","text":"I’ve settled on the minimal ontology change set: two requested receptor terms plus a supporting `left-handed Z-RNA binding` term, because the receptor branch consistently carries a ligand-binding child when no reusable one exists. I’m pulling the exact abstract text now so the temporary research note and new definitions are grounded in validated references.","time":{"start":1778987929960,"end":1778987935115}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778987935131,"sessionID":"ses_1cc16f0e6ffekDdP0f8Ru75kV9","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_orB5VqVQvCmmwKDWuxhYvZLH","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/references_cache/PMID_34678144.md","offset":1,"limit":180},"output":"<path>/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/references_cache/PMID_34678144.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: reference_id: PMID:34678144\n3: title: Phase separation drives RNA virus-induced activation of the NLRP6 inflammasome.\n4: authors:\n5: - Shen C\n6: - Li R\n7: - Negro R\n8: - Cheng J\n9: - Vora SM\n10: - Fu TM\n11: - Wang A\n12: - He K\n13: - Andreeva L\n14: - Gao P\n15: - Tian Z\n16: - Flavell RA\n17: - Zhu S\n18: - Wu H\n19: journal: Cell\n20: year: '2021'\n21: doi: 10.1016/j.cell.2021.09.032\n22: keywords:\n23: - Amino Acid Sequence\n24: - Animals\n25: - CARD Signaling Adaptor Proteins/metabolism\n26: - Hepatocytes/virology\n27: - Inflammasomes/metabolism\n28: - Intestines/virology\n29: - Intrinsically Disordered Proteins/chemistry\n30: - Lipopolysaccharides/metabolism\n31: - Liver/virology\n32: - Mice\n33: - Polylysine/metabolism\n34: - Protein Binding\n35: - RNA Viruses/physiology\n36: - \"RNA, Double-Stranded/metabolism\"\n37: - \"Receptors, Cell Surface/chemistry, metabolism\"\n38: - Signal Transduction\n39: - Teichoic Acids/metabolism\n40: content_type: abstract_only\n41: ---\n42: \n43: # Phase separation drives RNA virus-induced activation of the NLRP6 inflammasome.\n44: **Authors:** Shen C, Li R, Negro R, Cheng J, Vora SM, Fu TM, Wang A, He K, Andreeva L, Gao P, Tian Z, Flavell RA, Zhu S, Wu H\n45: **Journal:** Cell (2021)\n46: **DOI:** [10.1016/j.cell.2021.09.032](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.cell.2021.09.032)\n47: \n48: ## Content\n49: \n50: 1. Cell. 2021 Nov 11;184(23):5759-5774.e20. doi: 10.1016/j.cell.2021.09.032. Epub\n51:  2021 Oct 21.\n52: \n53: Phase separation drives RNA virus-induced activation of the NLRP6 inflammasome.\n54: \n55: Shen C(1), Li R(2), Negro R(3), Cheng J(2), Vora SM(1), Fu TM(4), Wang A(2), He \n56: K(2), Andreeva L(1), Gao P(5), Tian Z(2), Flavell RA(6), Zhu S(7), Wu H(8).\n57: \n58: Author information:\n59: (1)Department of Biological Chemistry and Molecular Pharmacology, Harvard \n60: Medical School, Boston, MA 02115, USA; Program in Cellular and Molecular \n61: Medicine, Boston Children's Hospital, Boston, MA 02115, USA.\n62: (2)Hefei National Laboratory for Physical Sciences at Microscale, the CAS Key \n63: Laboratory of Innate Immunity and Chronic Disease, School of Basic Medical \n64: Sciences, Division of Life Sciences and Medicine, University of Science and \n65: Technology of China, Hefei 230027, China; Institute of Immunology, University of \n66: Science and Technology of China, Hefei, China.\n67: (3)Department of Biological Chemistry and Molecular Pharmacology, Harvard \n68: Medical School, Boston, MA 02115, USA; Program in Cellular and Molecular \n69: Medicine, Boston Children's Hospital, Boston, MA 02115, USA; National Institute \n70: of Gastroenterology, \"S. de Bellis\" Research Hospital, Castellana Grotte, Bari \n71: 70013, Italy.\n72: (4)Department of Biological Chemistry and Molecular Pharmacology, Harvard \n73: Medical School, Boston, MA 02115, USA; Program in Cellular and Molecular \n74: Medicine, Boston Children's Hospital, Boston, MA 02115, USA; Department of \n75: Biological Chemistry and Pharmacology, The Ohio State University, Columbus, OH \n76: 43210, USA; The Ohio State University Comprehensive Cancer Center, Columbus, OH \n77: 43210, USA.\n78: (5)CAS Key Laboratory of Infection and Immunity, CAS Center for Excellence in \n79: Biomacromolecules, Institute of Biophysics, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Beijing \n80: 100101, China.\n81: (6)Department of Immunobiology, Yale School of Medicine, New Haven, CT, USA; \n82: Howard Hughes Medical Institute, New Haven, CT, USA.\n83: (7)Hefei National Laboratory for Physical Sciences at Microscale, the CAS Key \n84: Laboratory of Innate Immunity and Chronic Disease, School of Basic Medical \n85: Sciences, Division of Life Sciences and Medicine, University of Science and \n86: Technology of China, Hefei 230027, China; Institute of Immunology, University of \n87: Science and Technology of China, Hefei, China. Electronic address: \n88: zhushu@ustc.edu.cn.\n89: (8)Department of Biological Chemistry and Molecular Pharmacology, Harvard \n90: Medical School, Boston, MA 02115, USA; Program in Cellular and Molecular \n91: Medicine, Boston Children's Hospital, Boston, MA 02115, USA. Electronic address: \n92: wu@crystal.harvard.edu.\n93: \n94: Comment in\n95:     Cell Res. 2022 Feb;32(2):113-114. doi: 10.1038/s41422-021-00594-7.\n96: \n97: NLRP6 is important in host defense by inducing functional outcomes including \n98: inflammasome activation and interferon production. Here, we show that NLRP6 \n99: undergoes liquid-liquid phase separation (LLPS) upon interaction with \n100: double-stranded RNA (dsRNA) in vitro and in cells, and an intrinsically \n101: disordered poly-lysine sequence (K350-354) of NLRP6 is important for multivalent \n102: interactions, phase separation, and inflammasome activation. Nlrp6-deficient or \n103: Nlrp6K350-354A mutant mice show reduced inflammasome activation upon mouse \n104: hepatitis virus or rotavirus infection, and in steady state stimulated by \n105: intestinal microbiota, implicating NLRP6 LLPS in anti-microbial immunity. \n106: Recruitment of ASC via helical assembly solidifies NLRP6 condensates, and ASC \n107: further recruits and activates caspase-1. Lipoteichoic acid, a known NLRP6 \n108: ligand, also promotes NLRP6 LLPS, and DHX15, a helicase in NLRP6-induced \n109: interferon signaling, co-forms condensates with NLRP6 and dsRNA. Thus, LLPS of \n110: NLRP6 is a common response to ligand stimulation, which serves to direct NLRP6 \n111: to distinct functional outcomes depending on the cellular context.\n112: \n113: Copyright © 2021 Elsevier Inc. All rights reserved.\n114: \n115: DOI: 10.1016/j.cell.2021.09.032\n116: PMCID: PMC8643277\n117: PMID: 34678144 [Indexed for MEDLINE]\n118: \n119: Conflict of interest statement: Declaration of interests The authors declare no \n120: competing interests.\n\n(End of file - total 120 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nreference_id: PMID:34678144\ntitle: Phase separation drives RNA virus-induced activation of the NLRP6 inflammasome.\nauthors:\n- Shen C\n- Li R\n- Negro R\n- Cheng J\n- Vora SM\n- Fu TM\n- Wang A\n- He K\n- Andreeva L\n- Gao P\n- Tian Z\n- Flavell RA\n- Zhu S\n- Wu H\njournal: Cell\nyear: '2021'","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"references_cache/PMID_34678144.md","time":{"start":1778987935095,"end":1778987935119}},"id":"prt_e33f1a56b001Z86L7ORNxCC8xY","sessionID":"ses_1cc16f0e6ffekDdP0f8Ru75kV9","messageID":"msg_e33f16bca001fdx5OWwvCajYcx"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778987935131,"sessionID":"ses_1cc16f0e6ffekDdP0f8Ru75kV9","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_vGGEqMOHyl1aEjnu2xtT0hUT","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/references_cache/PMID_23273991.md","offset":1,"limit":140},"output":"<path>/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/references_cache/PMID_23273991.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: reference_id: PMID:23273991\n3: title: \"Structural basis for dsRNA recognition, filament formation, and antiviral signal activation by MDA5.\"\n4: authors:\n5: - Wu B\n6: - Peisley A\n7: - Richards C\n8: - Yao H\n9: - Zeng X\n10: - Lin C\n11: - Chu F\n12: - Walz T\n13: - Hur S\n14: journal: Cell\n15: year: '2013'\n16: doi: 10.1016/j.cell.2012.11.048\n17: keywords:\n18: - Amino Acid Sequence\n19: - \"DEAD-box RNA Helicases/chemistry, metabolism\"\n20: - Humans\n21: - \"Interferon-Induced Helicase, IFIH1\"\n22: - \"Models, Molecular\"\n23: - Molecular Sequence Data\n24: - \"Protein Structure, Tertiary\"\n25: - \"RNA, Double-Stranded/chemistry, metabolism\"\n26: - \"Receptors, Retinoic Acid/chemistry, metabolism\"\n27: - Sequence Alignment\n28: - X-Ray Diffraction\n29: content_type: abstract_only\n30: ---\n31: \n32: # Structural basis for dsRNA recognition, filament formation, and antiviral signal activation by MDA5.\n33: **Authors:** Wu B, Peisley A, Richards C, Yao H, Zeng X, Lin C, Chu F, Walz T, Hur S\n34: **Journal:** Cell (2013)\n35: **DOI:** [10.1016/j.cell.2012.11.048](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.cell.2012.11.048)\n36: \n37: ## Content\n38: \n39: 1. Cell. 2013 Jan 17;152(1-2):276-89. doi: 10.1016/j.cell.2012.11.048. Epub 2012 \n40: Dec 27.\n41: \n42: Structural basis for dsRNA recognition, filament formation, and antiviral signal \n43: activation by MDA5.\n44: \n45: Wu B(1), Peisley A, Richards C, Yao H, Zeng X, Lin C, Chu F, Walz T, Hur S.\n46: \n47: Author information:\n48: (1)Department of Biological Chemistry and Molecular Pharmacology, Harvard \n49: Medical School, Boston, MA 02115, USA.\n50: \n51: MDA5, a viral double-stranded RNA (dsRNA) receptor, shares sequence similarity \n52: and signaling pathways with RIG-I yet plays essential functions in antiviral \n53: immunity through distinct specificity for viral RNA. Revealing the molecular \n54: basis for the functional divergence, we report here the crystal structure \n55: of MDA5 bound to dsRNA, which shows how, using the same domain architecture, \n56: MDA5 recognizes the internal duplex structure, whereas RIG-I recognizes the \n57: terminus of dsRNA. We further show that MDA5 uses direct protein-protein \n58: contacts to stack along dsRNA in a head-to-tail arrangement, and that the \n59: signaling domain (tandem CARD), which decorates the outside of the core MDA5 \n60: filament, also has an intrinsic propensity to oligomerize into an elongated \n61: structure that activates the signaling adaptor, MAVS. These data support a model \n62: in which MDA5 uses long dsRNA as a signaling platform to cooperatively assemble \n63: the core filament, which in turn promotes stochastic assembly of the tandem CARD \n64: oligomers for signaling.\n65: \n66: Copyright © 2013 Elsevier Inc. All rights reserved.\n67: \n68: DOI: 10.1016/j.cell.2012.11.048\n69: PMID: 23273991 [Indexed for MEDLINE]\n\n(End of file - total 69 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nreference_id: PMID:23273991\ntitle: \"Structural basis for dsRNA recognition, filament formation, and antiviral signal activation by MDA5.\"\nauthors:\n- Wu B\n- Peisley A\n- Richards C\n- Yao H\n- Zeng X\n- Lin C\n- Chu F\n- Walz T\n- Hur S\njournal: Cell\nyear: '2013'\ndoi: 10.1016/j.cell.2012.11.048\nkeywords:\n- Amino Acid Sequence\n- \"DEAD-box RNA Helicases/chemistry, metabolism\"\n- Humans","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"references_cache/PMID_23273991.md","time":{"start":1778987935101,"end":1778987935123}},"id":"prt_e33f1a57a001609vdjtkKKPQM8","sessionID":"ses_1cc16f0e6ffekDdP0f8Ru75kV9","messageID":"msg_e33f16bca001fdx5OWwvCajYcx"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778987935132,"sessionID":"ses_1cc16f0e6ffekDdP0f8Ru75kV9","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_FzJSOCcZ8Hy2q7R4BkafImEU","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/references_cache/PMID_32200799.md","offset":1,"limit":160},"output":"<path>/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/references_cache/PMID_32200799.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: reference_id: PMID:32200799\n3: title: Influenza Virus Z-RNAs Induce ZBP1-Mediated Necroptosis.\n4: authors:\n5: - Zhang T\n6: - Yin C\n7: - Boyd DF\n8: - Quarato G\n9: - Ingram JP\n10: - Shubina M\n11: - Ragan KB\n12: - Ishizuka T\n13: - Crawford JC\n14: - Tummers B\n15: - Rodriguez DA\n16: - Xue J\n17: - Peri S\n18: - Kaiser WJ\n19: - López CB\n20: - Xu Y\n21: - Upton JW\n22: - Thomas PG\n23: - Green DR\n24: - Balachandran S\n25: journal: Cell\n26: year: '2020'\n27: doi: 10.1016/j.cell.2020.02.050\n28: keywords:\n29: - Animals\n30: - Apoptosis/genetics\n31: - Cell Death/genetics\n32: - \"Cell Line, Tumor\"\n33: - Female\n34: - \"Influenza A virus/genetics, metabolism\"\n35: - Male\n36: - Mice\n37: - \"Mice, Inbred C57BL\"\n38: - Necroptosis/genetics\n39: - Necrosis/metabolism\n40: - Phosphorylation\n41: - Protein Kinases/metabolism\n42: - RNA/metabolism\n43: - \"RNA, Double-Stranded/genetics, metabolism\"\n44: - \"RNA-Binding Proteins/genetics, metabolism\"\n45: - \"Receptor-Interacting Protein Serine-Threonine Kinases/metabolism, physiology\"\n46: content_type: abstract_only\n47: ---\n48: \n49: # Influenza Virus Z-RNAs Induce ZBP1-Mediated Necroptosis.\n50: **Authors:** Zhang T, Yin C, Boyd DF, Quarato G, Ingram JP, Shubina M, Ragan KB, Ishizuka T, Crawford JC, Tummers B, Rodriguez DA, Xue J, Peri S, Kaiser WJ, López CB, Xu Y, Upton JW, Thomas PG, Green DR, Balachandran S\n51: **Journal:** Cell (2020)\n52: **DOI:** [10.1016/j.cell.2020.02.050](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.cell.2020.02.050)\n53: \n54: ## Content\n55: \n56: 1. Cell. 2020 Mar 19;180(6):1115-1129.e13. doi: 10.1016/j.cell.2020.02.050.\n57: \n58: Influenza Virus Z-RNAs Induce ZBP1-Mediated Necroptosis.\n59: \n60: Zhang T(1), Yin C(1), Boyd DF(2), Quarato G(2), Ingram JP(1), Shubina M(1), \n61: Ragan KB(3), Ishizuka T(4), Crawford JC(2), Tummers B(2), Rodriguez DA(2), Xue \n62: J(5), Peri S(1), Kaiser WJ(6), López CB(5), Xu Y(4), Upton JW(3), Thomas PG(2), \n63: Green DR(2), Balachandran S(7).\n64: \n65: Author information:\n66: (1)Blood Cell Development and Function Program, Fox Chase Cancer Center, \n67: Philadelphia, PA, USA.\n68: (2)Department of Immunology, St. Jude Children's Research Hospital, Memphis, TN, \n69: USA.\n70: (3)Department of Molecular Biosciences, LaMontagne Center for Infectious \n71: Disease, University of Texas, Austin, Austin, TX, USA.\n72: (4)Division of Chemistry, Department of Medical Sciences, Faculty of Medicine, \n73: University of Miyazaki, 5200 Kihara, Kiyotake, Miyazaki 889-1692, Japan.\n74: (5)Department of Pathobiology, School of Veterinary Medicine, University of \n75: Pennsylvania, Philadelphia, PA, USA.\n76: (6)University of Texas Health Sciences Center, San Antonio, San Antonio, TX, \n77: USA.\n78: (7)Blood Cell Development and Function Program, Fox Chase Cancer Center, \n79: Philadelphia, PA, USA. Electronic address: siddharth.balachandran@fccc.edu.\n80: \n81: Influenza A virus (IAV) is a lytic RNA virus that triggers receptor-interacting \n82: serine/threonine-protein kinase 3 (RIPK3)-mediated pathways of apoptosis and \n83: mixed lineage kinase domain-like pseudokinase (MLKL)-dependent necroptosis in \n84: infected cells. ZBP1 initiates RIPK3-driven cell death by sensing IAV RNA and \n85: activating RIPK3. Here, we show that replicating IAV generates Z-RNAs, which \n86: activate ZBP1 in the nucleus of infected cells. ZBP1 then initiates \n87: RIPK3-mediated MLKL activation in the nucleus, resulting in nuclear envelope \n88: disruption, leakage of DNA into the cytosol, and eventual necroptosis. Cell \n89: death induced by nuclear MLKL was a potent activator of neutrophils, a cell type \n90: known to drive inflammatory pathology in virulent IAV disease. Consequently, \n91: MLKL-deficient mice manifest reduced nuclear disruption of lung epithelia, \n92: decreased neutrophil recruitment into infected lungs, and increased survival \n93: following a lethal dose of IAV. These results implicate Z-RNA as a new \n94: pathogen-associated molecular pattern and describe a ZBP1-initiated \n95: nucleus-to-plasma membrane \"inside-out\" death pathway with potentially \n96: pathogenic consequences in severe cases of influenza.\n97: \n98: Copyright © 2020 Elsevier Inc. All rights reserved.\n99: \n100: DOI: 10.1016/j.cell.2020.02.050\n101: PMCID: PMC7153753\n102: PMID: 32200799 [Indexed for MEDLINE]\n103: \n104: Conflict of interest statement: Declaration of Interests The authors declare no \n105: competing interests.\n\n(End of file - total 105 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nreference_id: PMID:32200799\ntitle: Influenza Virus Z-RNAs Induce ZBP1-Mediated Necroptosis.\nauthors:\n- Zhang T\n- Yin C\n- Boyd DF\n- Quarato G\n- Ingram JP\n- Shubina M\n- Ragan KB\n- Ishizuka T\n- Crawford JC\n- Tummers B\n- Rodriguez DA\n- Xue J\n- Peri S\n- Kaiser WJ\n- López CB\n- Xu Y","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"references_cache/PMID_32200799.md","time":{"start":1778987935106,"end":1778987935127}},"id":"prt_e33f1a57f001934A57WmBBxVhH","sessionID":"ses_1cc16f0e6ffekDdP0f8Ru75kV9","messageID":"msg_e33f16bca001fdx5OWwvCajYcx"}}
