{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778987991064,"sessionID":"ses_1cc16f0e6ffekDdP0f8Ru75kV9","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_nlWLTVLPhT8ZgsP4Jvq4SNz5","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/terms/issue_32046.obo\n+[Term]\n+id: GO:7770072\n+name: left-handed Z-RNA binding\n+namespace: molecular_function\n+def: \"Binding to left-handed Z-RNA, a left-handed double-helical conformation of RNA in which the phosphate backbone zigzags.\" [PMID:32200799]\n+synonym: \"Z-RNA binding\" EXACT []\n+is_a: GO:0003725 ! double-stranded RNA binding\n+property_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/32046\" xsd:anyURI\n+created_by: dragon-ai-agent\n+creation_date: 2026-05-17T03:18:10Z\n+\n+[Term]\n+id: GO:7770073\n+name: double-stranded RNA immune receptor activity\n+namespace: molecular_function\n+def: \"Combining with double-stranded RNA and transmitting the signal to initiate an innate immune response.\" [PMID:33243852, PMID:34678144, PMID:23273991]\n+synonym: \"dsRNA immune receptor activity\" EXACT []\n+is_a: GO:0038187 ! pattern recognition receptor activity\n+relationship: has_part GO:0003725 ! double-stranded RNA binding\n+property_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/32046\" xsd:anyURI\n+created_by: dragon-ai-agent\n+creation_date: 2026-05-17T03:18:10Z\n+\n+[Term]\n+id: GO:7770074\n+name: left-handed Z-RNA immune receptor activity\n+namespace: molecular_function\n+def: \"Combining with left-handed Z-RNA and transmitting the signal to initiate an innate immune response. Z-RNA is a left-handed double-helical conformation of RNA in which the phosphate backbone zigzags.\" [PMID:32200799]\n+synonym: \"Z-RNA immune receptor activity\" EXACT []\n+is_a: GO:7770073 ! double-stranded RNA immune receptor activity\n+relationship: has_part GO:7770072 ! left-handed Z-RNA binding\n+property_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/32046\" xsd:anyURI\n+created_by: dragon-ai-agent\n+creation_date: 2026-05-17T03:18:10Z\n*** Add File: /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n+## PMID:33243852 \"Human NLRP1 is a sensor for double-stranded RNA.\"\n+\n+Human NLRP1 directly senses long double-stranded RNA and is therefore suitable support for a dsRNA-specific innate immune receptor activity term.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:33243852 \"Biochemical studies revealed that NLRP1 binds dsRNA through its leucine-rich repeat domain, resulting in its NACHT domain gaining adenosine triphosphatase activity. Altogether, these results establish human NLRP1 as a direct sensor for dsRNA and thus RNA virus infection.\"\n+    - NLRP1 directly binds dsRNA.\n+    - dsRNA sensing initiates innate immune signaling.\n+\n+## PMID:34678144 \"Phase separation drives RNA virus-induced activation of the NLRP6 inflammasome.\"\n+\n+NLRP6 responds to dsRNA and this ligand interaction drives innate immune signaling outputs, supporting the broader dsRNA immune receptor class.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:34678144 \"Here, we show that NLRP6 undergoes liquid-liquid phase separation (LLPS) upon interaction with double-stranded RNA (dsRNA) in vitro and in cells\"\n+    - NLRP6 interacts with dsRNA.\n+    - dsRNA binding is part of the activation mechanism for innate immune response signaling.\n+\n+## PMID:23273991 \"Structural basis for dsRNA recognition, filament formation, and antiviral signal activation by MDA5.\"\n+\n+MDA5 is an established antiviral dsRNA receptor and provides strong support for the requested receptor class.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:23273991 \"MDA5, a viral double-stranded RNA (dsRNA) receptor, shares sequence similarity and signaling pathways with RIG-I yet plays essential functions in antiviral immunity through distinct specificity for viral RNA.\"\n+    - MDA5 is explicitly described as a viral dsRNA receptor.\n+    - The receptor activity is tied to antiviral innate immunity.\n+\n+## PMID:32200799 \"Influenza Virus Z-RNAs Induce ZBP1-Mediated Necroptosis.\"\n+\n+This paper identifies Z-RNA as a pathogen-associated molecular pattern and shows that ZBP1 is activated by it, supporting both a Z-RNA binding term and a child immune receptor activity term.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:32200799 \"Here, we show that replicating IAV generates Z-RNAs, which activate ZBP1 in the nucleus of infected cells.\"\n+    - ZBP1 is activated by Z-RNA.\n+    - Z-RNA acts as a ligand for innate immune signaling.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:32200799 \"These results implicate Z-RNA as a new pathogen-associated molecular pattern\"\n+    - Z-RNA is a pathogen-associated molecular pattern.\n+    - That supports placement under pattern recognition receptor activity.\n*** Add File: /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/DESIGN_PATTERNS.md\n+# Issue #32046 design pattern notes\n+\n+Relevant pattern: `docs/patterns/signaling_receptor_activity_by_input.md`\n+\n+- This pattern models ligand-specific receptor activities as children of `GO:0038023 ! signaling receptor activity` with an equivalence to `has_primary_input some {input}`.\n+- Existing immune receptor children such as `GO:0001875 ! lipopolysaccharide immune receptor activity`, `GO:0016019 ! peptidoglycan immune receptor activity`, and `GO:0070892 ! lipoteichoic acid immune receptor activity` also include a `has_part` relation to the corresponding ligand-binding activity.\n+\n+Application to this issue:\n+\n+- `double-stranded RNA immune receptor activity` fits the lexical and definitional form of existing ligand-specific immune receptor terms.\n+- Because dsRNA is represented in GO via `GO:0003725 ! double-stranded RNA binding`, the new receptor term can follow precedent with `relationship: has_part GO:0003725`.\n+- The full logical pattern using `has_primary_input` is not applied here because the issue explicitly notes limitations around representing these large RNA ligands for receptor-term compositional modeling, and there is no established external term available locally for left-handed Z-RNA.\n+- `left-handed Z-RNA immune receptor activity` is modeled as a child of the broader dsRNA immune receptor activity term with a supporting new binding term `left-handed Z-RNA binding`.\n+\n+Conclusion:\n+\n+- Use weaker asserted axioms (`is_a` plus `has_part`) consistent with existing immune receptor precedent when the exact ligand class cannot be cleanly expressed in the standard receptor-by-input pattern.\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA terms/issue_32046.obo\nA RESEARCH.md\nA DESIGN_PATTERNS.md","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/terms/issue_32046.obo\n===================================================================\n--- /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/terms/issue_32046.obo\n+++ /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/terms/issue_32046.obo\n@@ -0,0 +1,34 @@\n+[Term]\n+id: GO:7770072\n+name: left-handed Z-RNA binding\n+namespace: molecular_function\n+def: \"Binding to left-handed Z-RNA, a left-handed double-helical conformation of RNA in which the phosphate backbone zigzags.\" [PMID:32200799]\n+synonym: \"Z-RNA binding\" EXACT []\n+is_a: GO:0003725 ! double-stranded RNA binding\n+property_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/32046\" xsd:anyURI\n+created_by: dragon-ai-agent\n+creation_date: 2026-05-17T03:18:10Z\n+\n+[Term]\n+id: GO:7770073\n+name: double-stranded RNA immune receptor activity\n+namespace: molecular_function\n+def: \"Combining with double-stranded RNA and transmitting the signal to initiate an innate immune response.\" [PMID:33243852, PMID:34678144, PMID:23273991]\n+synonym: \"dsRNA immune receptor activity\" EXACT []\n+is_a: GO:0038187 ! pattern recognition receptor activity\n+relationship: has_part GO:0003725 ! double-stranded RNA binding\n+property_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/32046\" xsd:anyURI\n+created_by: dragon-ai-agent\n+creation_date: 2026-05-17T03:18:10Z\n+\n+[Term]\n+id: GO:7770074\n+name: left-handed Z-RNA immune receptor activity\n+namespace: molecular_function\n+def: \"Combining with left-handed Z-RNA and transmitting the signal to initiate an innate immune response. Z-RNA is a left-handed double-helical conformation of RNA in which the phosphate backbone zigzags.\" [PMID:32200799]\n+synonym: \"Z-RNA immune receptor activity\" EXACT []\n+is_a: GO:7770073 ! double-stranded RNA immune receptor activity\n+relationship: has_part GO:7770072 ! left-handed Z-RNA binding\n+property_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/32046\" xsd:anyURI\n+created_by: dragon-ai-agent\n+creation_date: 2026-05-17T03:18:10Z\n\nIndex: /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n===================================================================\n--- /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n+++ /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n@@ -0,0 +1,35 @@\n+## PMID:33243852 \"Human NLRP1 is a sensor for double-stranded RNA.\"\n+\n+Human NLRP1 directly senses long double-stranded RNA and is therefore suitable support for a dsRNA-specific innate immune receptor activity term.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:33243852 \"Biochemical studies revealed that NLRP1 binds dsRNA through its leucine-rich repeat domain, resulting in its NACHT domain gaining adenosine triphosphatase activity. Altogether, these results establish human NLRP1 as a direct sensor for dsRNA and thus RNA virus infection.\"\n+    - NLRP1 directly binds dsRNA.\n+    - dsRNA sensing initiates innate immune signaling.\n+\n+## PMID:34678144 \"Phase separation drives RNA virus-induced activation of the NLRP6 inflammasome.\"\n+\n+NLRP6 responds to dsRNA and this ligand interaction drives innate immune signaling outputs, supporting the broader dsRNA immune receptor class.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:34678144 \"Here, we show that NLRP6 undergoes liquid-liquid phase separation (LLPS) upon interaction with double-stranded RNA (dsRNA) in vitro and in cells\"\n+    - NLRP6 interacts with dsRNA.\n+    - dsRNA binding is part of the activation mechanism for innate immune response signaling.\n+\n+## PMID:23273991 \"Structural basis for dsRNA recognition, filament formation, and antiviral signal activation by MDA5.\"\n+\n+MDA5 is an established antiviral dsRNA receptor and provides strong support for the requested receptor class.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:23273991 \"MDA5, a viral double-stranded RNA (dsRNA) receptor, shares sequence similarity and signaling pathways with RIG-I yet plays essential functions in antiviral immunity through distinct specificity for viral RNA.\"\n+    - MDA5 is explicitly described as a viral dsRNA receptor.\n+    - The receptor activity is tied to antiviral innate immunity.\n+\n+## PMID:32200799 \"Influenza Virus Z-RNAs Induce ZBP1-Mediated Necroptosis.\"\n+\n+This paper identifies Z-RNA as a pathogen-associated molecular pattern and shows that ZBP1 is activated by it, supporting both a Z-RNA binding term and a child immune receptor activity term.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:32200799 \"Here, we show that replicating IAV generates Z-RNAs, which activate ZBP1 in the nucleus of infected cells.\"\n+    - ZBP1 is activated by Z-RNA.\n+    - Z-RNA acts as a ligand for innate immune signaling.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:32200799 \"These results implicate Z-RNA as a new pathogen-associated molecular pattern\"\n+    - Z-RNA is a pathogen-associated molecular pattern.\n+    - That supports placement under pattern recognition receptor activity.\n\nIndex: /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/DESIGN_PATTERNS.md\n===================================================================\n--- /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/DESIGN_PATTERNS.md\n+++ /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/DESIGN_PATTERNS.md\n@@ -0,0 +1,17 @@\n+# Issue #32046 design pattern notes\n+\n+Relevant pattern: `docs/patterns/signaling_receptor_activity_by_input.md`\n+\n+- This pattern models ligand-specific receptor activities as children of `GO:0038023 ! signaling receptor activity` with an equivalence to `has_primary_input some {input}`.\n+- Existing immune receptor children such as `GO:0001875 ! lipopolysaccharide immune receptor activity`, `GO:0016019 ! peptidoglycan immune receptor activity`, and `GO:0070892 ! lipoteichoic acid immune receptor activity` also include a `has_part` relation to the corresponding ligand-binding activity.\n+\n+Application to this issue:\n+\n+- `double-stranded RNA immune receptor activity` fits the lexical and definitional form of existing ligand-specific immune receptor terms.\n+- Because dsRNA is represented in GO via `GO:0003725 ! double-stranded RNA binding`, the new receptor term can follow precedent with `relationship: has_part GO:0003725`.\n+- The full logical pattern using `has_primary_input` is not applied here because the issue explicitly notes limitations around representing these large RNA ligands for receptor-term compositional modeling, and there is no established external term available locally for left-handed Z-RNA.\n+- `left-handed Z-RNA immune receptor activity` is modeled as a child of the broader dsRNA immune receptor activity term with a supporting new binding term `left-handed Z-RNA binding`.\n+\n+Conclusion:\n+\n+- Use weaker asserted axioms (`is_a` plus `has_part`) consistent with existing immune receptor precedent when the exact ligand class cannot be cleanly expressed in the standard receptor-by-input pattern.\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/terms/issue_32046.obo","relativePath":"terms/issue_32046.obo","type":"add","patch":"Index: /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/terms/issue_32046.obo\n===================================================================\n--- /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/terms/issue_32046.obo\n+++ /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/terms/issue_32046.obo\n@@ -0,0 +1,34 @@\n+[Term]\n+id: GO:7770072\n+name: left-handed Z-RNA binding\n+namespace: molecular_function\n+def: \"Binding to left-handed Z-RNA, a left-handed double-helical conformation of RNA in which the phosphate backbone zigzags.\" [PMID:32200799]\n+synonym: \"Z-RNA binding\" EXACT []\n+is_a: GO:0003725 ! double-stranded RNA binding\n+property_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/32046\" xsd:anyURI\n+created_by: dragon-ai-agent\n+creation_date: 2026-05-17T03:18:10Z\n+\n+[Term]\n+id: GO:7770073\n+name: double-stranded RNA immune receptor activity\n+namespace: molecular_function\n+def: \"Combining with double-stranded RNA and transmitting the signal to initiate an innate immune response.\" [PMID:33243852, PMID:34678144, PMID:23273991]\n+synonym: \"dsRNA immune receptor activity\" EXACT []\n+is_a: GO:0038187 ! pattern recognition receptor activity\n+relationship: has_part GO:0003725 ! double-stranded RNA binding\n+property_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/32046\" xsd:anyURI\n+created_by: dragon-ai-agent\n+creation_date: 2026-05-17T03:18:10Z\n+\n+[Term]\n+id: GO:7770074\n+name: left-handed Z-RNA immune receptor activity\n+namespace: molecular_function\n+def: \"Combining with left-handed Z-RNA and transmitting the signal to initiate an innate immune response. Z-RNA is a left-handed double-helical conformation of RNA in which the phosphate backbone zigzags.\" [PMID:32200799]\n+synonym: \"Z-RNA immune receptor activity\" EXACT []\n+is_a: GO:7770073 ! double-stranded RNA immune receptor activity\n+relationship: has_part GO:7770072 ! left-handed Z-RNA binding\n+property_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/32046\" xsd:anyURI\n+created_by: dragon-ai-agent\n+creation_date: 2026-05-17T03:18:10Z\n","additions":34,"deletions":0},{"filePath":"/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md","relativePath":"RESEARCH.md","type":"add","patch":"Index: /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n===================================================================\n--- /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n+++ /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n@@ -0,0 +1,35 @@\n+## PMID:33243852 \"Human NLRP1 is a sensor for double-stranded RNA.\"\n+\n+Human NLRP1 directly senses long double-stranded RNA and is therefore suitable support for a dsRNA-specific innate immune receptor activity term.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:33243852 \"Biochemical studies revealed that NLRP1 binds dsRNA through its leucine-rich repeat domain, resulting in its NACHT domain gaining adenosine triphosphatase activity. Altogether, these results establish human NLRP1 as a direct sensor for dsRNA and thus RNA virus infection.\"\n+    - NLRP1 directly binds dsRNA.\n+    - dsRNA sensing initiates innate immune signaling.\n+\n+## PMID:34678144 \"Phase separation drives RNA virus-induced activation of the NLRP6 inflammasome.\"\n+\n+NLRP6 responds to dsRNA and this ligand interaction drives innate immune signaling outputs, supporting the broader dsRNA immune receptor class.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:34678144 \"Here, we show that NLRP6 undergoes liquid-liquid phase separation (LLPS) upon interaction with double-stranded RNA (dsRNA) in vitro and in cells\"\n+    - NLRP6 interacts with dsRNA.\n+    - dsRNA binding is part of the activation mechanism for innate immune response signaling.\n+\n+## PMID:23273991 \"Structural basis for dsRNA recognition, filament formation, and antiviral signal activation by MDA5.\"\n+\n+MDA5 is an established antiviral dsRNA receptor and provides strong support for the requested receptor class.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:23273991 \"MDA5, a viral double-stranded RNA (dsRNA) receptor, shares sequence similarity and signaling pathways with RIG-I yet plays essential functions in antiviral immunity through distinct specificity for viral RNA.\"\n+    - MDA5 is explicitly described as a viral dsRNA receptor.\n+    - The receptor activity is tied to antiviral innate immunity.\n+\n+## PMID:32200799 \"Influenza Virus Z-RNAs Induce ZBP1-Mediated Necroptosis.\"\n+\n+This paper identifies Z-RNA as a pathogen-associated molecular pattern and shows that ZBP1 is activated by it, supporting both a Z-RNA binding term and a child immune receptor activity term.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:32200799 \"Here, we show that replicating IAV generates Z-RNAs, which activate ZBP1 in the nucleus of infected cells.\"\n+    - ZBP1 is activated by Z-RNA.\n+    - Z-RNA acts as a ligand for innate immune signaling.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:32200799 \"These results implicate Z-RNA as a new pathogen-associated molecular pattern\"\n+    - Z-RNA is a pathogen-associated molecular pattern.\n+    - That supports placement under pattern recognition receptor activity.\n","additions":35,"deletions":0},{"filePath":"/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/DESIGN_PATTERNS.md","relativePath":"DESIGN_PATTERNS.md","type":"add","patch":"Index: /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/DESIGN_PATTERNS.md\n===================================================================\n--- /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/DESIGN_PATTERNS.md\n+++ /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/DESIGN_PATTERNS.md\n@@ -0,0 +1,17 @@\n+# Issue #32046 design pattern notes\n+\n+Relevant pattern: `docs/patterns/signaling_receptor_activity_by_input.md`\n+\n+- This pattern models ligand-specific receptor activities as children of `GO:0038023 ! signaling receptor activity` with an equivalence to `has_primary_input some {input}`.\n+- Existing immune receptor children such as `GO:0001875 ! lipopolysaccharide immune receptor activity`, `GO:0016019 ! peptidoglycan immune receptor activity`, and `GO:0070892 ! lipoteichoic acid immune receptor activity` also include a `has_part` relation to the corresponding ligand-binding activity.\n+\n+Application to this issue:\n+\n+- `double-stranded RNA immune receptor activity` fits the lexical and definitional form of existing ligand-specific immune receptor terms.\n+- Because dsRNA is represented in GO via `GO:0003725 ! double-stranded RNA binding`, the new receptor term can follow precedent with `relationship: has_part GO:0003725`.\n+- The full logical pattern using `has_primary_input` is not applied here because the issue explicitly notes limitations around representing these large RNA ligands for receptor-term compositional modeling, and there is no established external term available locally for left-handed Z-RNA.\n+- `left-handed Z-RNA immune receptor activity` is modeled as a child of the broader dsRNA immune receptor activity term with a supporting new binding term `left-handed Z-RNA binding`.\n+\n+Conclusion:\n+\n+- Use weaker asserted axioms (`is_a` plus `has_part`) consistent with existing immune receptor precedent when the exact ligand class cannot be cleanly expressed in the standard receptor-by-input pattern.\n","additions":17,"deletions":0}],"diagnostics":{},"truncated":false},"title":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA terms/issue_32046.obo\nA RESEARCH.md\nA DESIGN_PATTERNS.md","time":{"start":1778987991051,"end":1778987991061}},"id":"prt_e33f20ad7001IxYtoj4Lm9rtuB","sessionID":"ses_1cc16f0e6ffekDdP0f8Ru75kV9","messageID":"msg_e33f1fa77001U9VTZuHCP6P4gP"}}
